stylometry: with @risk you want to consider the output and get a low standard deviation and also consider your input results to make a decision. When running a simulation with 5 inputs you must use risk simtable to allow all five inputs to each be ran and then considered in the decision. Risk simtable allows you to put in the values of the 5 inputs and simulate for each. You run with 1000 itterations and 5 inputs; hit run and the conclusion will display in graphical formats to help you determine what to do. The data is analyzed by being able to look at each result at the same time, as stated above you must look at things like standard deviation for each, and consider the other outputs that each input results. It is great to be able to do a simulation with  5 inputs (or more) at the same time.
